			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">But my personal favorite, C.S. Friedman. He wrote the Black Sun Rising trilogy, probably the most creative, interesting, and just plain great books I've ever read.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Good was starting to think i was the only one who appreciated that series.  That series has prompted me with more re-reads than i care to admit to.  Seems like i understand the way the Fae works a little better with each reading and OMG is Tarrant not the best character you love to hate?
<br />

<br />
This series was one of my biggest surprises.  I have to say the cover caught my eye first.  Yaeh yeah i know, cant judge a book by its cover, but the cover did intrigue me enough to read the back.  Even after that i didnt seem to interested so it took me a couple months more of picking it up and reading the back whenever i was in the book store before i actually purchased it.
<br />

<br />
Im more into fantasy than sci-fi so i think thats what steered me clear at first.  Simply for the fact that the book refers to the lives of Humans that left Earth to colonize new planets in giant colony ships when the Earth began to die.  I was like "ehh, whats all this sci-fi stuff when there is a guy with a sword on the front cover?"  Well, the answers came fast as did the end of the book, leaving me yearning for the next one in the series.
<br />

<br />
A MUST READ</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
