			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">My two favorite authors are Robert Jordan and David (&amp; Leigh) Eddings.
<br />

<br />
Terry Goodkind is really good too, but his books are too patternized really, imo of course. It feels wrong to me that the focus is moved from the epic fight against the devil to a fight against a simple emperor (even though hes much more than just an emperor it still feels wrong to move from the source of all evil to a manmade conqueror).
<br />

<br />
I write a bit about the books after my recomendations, I try to keep from giving away anything important that would make it boring to read but if you already intend to read the book you might want to skip reading the rest of each paragraph.. I gave that text a color that should blend in very well with the backdrop so you dont accidently read any of it, just mark the text to be able to read it <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />
<br />

<br />

<br />
David &amp; Leigh Eddings' latest book "The Redemption of Althalus" is really a good read, nobody mentioned it so I figured I would. Like all David Eddings' books it sets a sedated pace for the story at first, paying attention to things mundane so you get familiar with the setting before he dives into the mystical and epic. This book is really very well written, the story is epic and interesting, hes really learned from his previous books imo. He had some problems with making a satisfactory ending in the previous books imo. <font color="#DEE3E7">The book is about Althalus who is the worlds best thief and the luckiest man in the world. He is approached by a man whos eyes seems to be on fire one day when hes just about run out of money and is offered a large sum of gold to steal a book from a house at the end of the world. But things dont go quite as planned when a godess imprisons him since he was chosen to do "Little things - saving the world, keeping the stars up in the sky where they belong, making sure that time keeps moving. Things like that."</font>
<br />

<br />
Since you like Terry Goodkind I would suggest trying Raymond E. Feist's "Riftwar saga", it begins with "Magician". Thats actually 2 books in one though, you can buy them seperatly if you can find them as "Magician: Apprentice" and "Magician: Master". I cant say exactly why but I would say that its fairly similar to the Sword of Truth series. It seems like a very bright serie to begin with but things gets worse as the world decents into the riftwar. <font color="#DEE3E7">The main character finds out hes adapted with magic and is learning just that in the kings castle when the great rift opens. He gets in the middle of things and is kidnapped and moved across the rift. My memory is a bit sketchy, I gave away the first book in the series to a friend and havent bothered with replacing it yet.</font>
<br />

<br />
Katherine Kerr's "Deverry" series is also slightly like the Sword of Truth series. Its about several stories from different times and how they weave together into a rather dark story. <font color="#DEE3E7">The books follow the destiny of 3 souls. It all begins when two fall in love with the third and one does both other souls wrong to gain her love. When things go horribly wrong he wovs to not rest until hes righted his wrongs. And the gods listen. The books describe a story about good and evil but is punctuated with stories of the past lives of the two souls he has hurt and how that effects things today. Like Jordans books things evolve throughout the books, weaving more and more stories into the series. He does tend to finish stories while hes introducing new once though.</font>
<br />

<br />
David Farland's "Runelord" series is very cool, I very much recomend his books even though it seems like hes stopped writing. Its a very fast paced and epic serie, and for those who likes to learn something it teaches a lot about ethics and morale. It has a lot of epic battles on a similar scale of those in the later books in the Wheel of Time. <font color="#DEE3E7">The books are about a wolflord whos forcing people to give up their best traits (strength, intelligence, etc) to him with magical means (by using runes - thus the title) and how he is about to conquer the world and turn into an immortal being from all the stamina hes stolen. The main good character that the book is following is the prince of one of the larger kingdoms and himself a runelord (but hasnt stolen the traits but received them from loving subjects, or purchased them for large sums). He is out traveling when he suddenly gets cut off by the wolflord's troops, when he sees the abominations that the troops contains he decides to try to ward off the attack by warning the town ahead of the army. After the wolflord crushes the city with ease the northern countries realize that he wont stop until he has taken over the world and starts to round up as many of their own runelords to ward off his attacks. It too evolves from the initial fights into an even more epic scale.</font><br />_________________<br /><center><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=360803" target="_blank" OnClick="javascript:window.open('http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=360803','','width=800,height=600'); return false"><img src="http://home.swipnet.se/Nulli-Secundis/pics/DahkarET.jpg" border="0" alt="Click here to inspect"></a></center></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
